Hi Flip,

You don't need bulk gauge fields to have a chirality problem. It's
completely generic that if you don't have singularities, you can't get
4D chiral fermions from extra dimensions. Once you orbifold the circle
to an interval, you are forced to pick opposite boundary conditions
for the left- and right-handed parts of your spinor. This is because
they are coupled by the kinetic term: your Lagrangian contains
something like psi d/dy chi, and d/dy is obviously odd. (Here psi and
chi are the two 4D Weyl spinors in the 5D spinor, y is the fifth
coordinate.) So one of psi and chi is odd, the other even. The mass
term also couples psi and chi, which tells you the bulk mass is odd
under the orbifolding, hence the strange-looking sign(phi).

Best,

Matt
